<DOC><DOCNO> AP880715-0096 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0957EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Norway-CopterCrash     07-15 0192</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Norway-Copter Crash,0198</SECOND><HEAD>Helicopter Makes Emergency Landing in North Sea, All Rescued</HEAD><DATELINE>STAVANGER, Norway (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A helicopter ferrying workers from anoffshore oil rig made an emergency landing in the North Sea today,and another helicopter rescued all 18 people who were aboard,officials said.   All the passengers and crew were safe, said officials at theNorwegian Rescue Center at Sola Airport near this coastal oilcenter.   Rescue center spokesman Inge Kavle said a Super Puma helicopterof the Norwegian Helicopter Service Company had to land in thewater about 80 miles southwest of Stavanger due to engine problems.   ``It was a controlled emergency landing and no crash,'' Kavlesaid.   The 16 passengers and two crew members were picked up fromrubber dinghies by a Sea King helicpter from the same company.   The Puma helicopter was on its way from the Ula oil rig when itran into trouble at 1:10 p.m.   It was the second time in three days that a helicopter made anemergency landing in the North Sea. On Wednesday, a helicopterditched east of Lerwick in the Shetland Islands. All 21 people onboard were rescued.</TEXT></DOC>